Adaptive Behavior publishes work on how adaptive behavior arises in animals and autonomous artificial systems, with particular interest in embodied, situated agents studied through simulation, robotics, and dynamical-systems modeling. Our paper fits this scope: we implement an embodied simulated agent that navigates a 3D environment under homeostatic pressure, and we use reinforcement learning to study how adaptive foraging behavior can become entrenched, destabilized, and reformed over time.

The work formalizes long-standing but largely metaphorical ideas—canalization, decanalization, and recanalization—into a concrete agent-based model, and it compares two homeostatic reward architectures (HRL vs. negative feedback) to determine whether temporary destabilization produces adaptive behavior in both. In doing so, it speaks to core Adaptive Behavior themes: homeostatic regulation, explore-exploit dynamics, learning under environmental change, and the interplay between agent architecture and behavioral flexibility.